		<img width="2500" height="1200" src="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-ai-weather.jpg" class="singlepostthumb wp-post-image" alt="" decoding="async" fetchpriority="high" srcset="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-ai-weather.jpg 2500w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-ai-weather-520x250.jpg 520w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-ai-weather-1200x576.jpg 1200w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-ai-weather-768x369.jpg 768w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-ai-weather-1536x737.jpg 1536w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-ai-weather-2048x983.jpg 2048w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-ai-weather-900x432.jpg 900w" sizes="(max-width: 2500px) 100vw, 2500px" /><div class="post-thumbnail-caption">Lightning strikes the British Columbia coast, as seen from a ferry traveling between communities. According to a 2014 study, roughly 75 percent of marine accidents during bad weather happen when container ships, ferries, and other big boats are in or approaching ports. Photo by hpbfotos/Alamy Stock Photo</div>
			<article class="main container col4">
								<header class="maincol">
										<h1 class="pagetitle">Marine Weather Forecasts Are Getting an AI Upgrade</h1>
										<h2 class="dek singlepagecontainer">Machine learning systems—powered by new data—are taking some of the guesswork out of maritime safety.</h2>
										<section class="singlebyline singlepagecontainer">
						<h3 class="invis">Authored by</h3>
						by  
										<a href="https://hakaimagazine.com/profiles/vanessa-minke-martin/" class="tagmanager" id="author_link_top" >Vanessa Minke-Martin</a>								<br/>
												</section>
					 
					<aside class="singlebydatewords singlepagecontainer">
						<h3 class="invis">Wordcount</h3>
						October 25, 2024 | 1,100 words, about 5 minutes
					</aside>

					
				</header>

				
